<TEXT>
after months of appearing paralyzed by 
president bushs high poll ratings the democrats have shifted into 
a campaign mode and begun to sound like a party ready to challenge 
bush in the 1992 election 
during weekend meetings in new orleans and indianapolis the 
democrats took on the popular republican president on a range of 
domestic issues including social security the environment 
abortion and education 
the partys newly aggressive stance was not arrived at easily 
it exposed the differing approaches of state party officials hungry 
for effective campaign issues and the congressional wing whose 
members must often search for compromises with their republican 
colleagues and the white house 
regardless of their differences on specific issues the 
democrats clearly agreed with party chairman ronald h browns 
assessment that the president has been getting a free ride and 
that it was time to challenge him 
the party officials gathered in indianapolis for a meeting of 
the democratic national committee while the elected democrats were 
in new orleans for a session convened by the democratic leadership 
council 
brown attended both meetings and was instrumental in pushing his 
party to endorse sen daniel patrick moynihans proposal to cut the 
social security payroll tax a plan some of moynihans fellow 
democrats flatly oppose 
im not concerned there is going to be a debate brown told 
a news conference on the closing day of the dnc meeting there 
ought to be a debate 
the chairman was asked if he would feel a litle uncomfortable 
with the stand of his party if he were an elected official say 
sen lloyd bentsen of texas who is decidedly unethusiastic about 
the proposal by his new york colleague 
i think id feel good that my national party was committed to 
winning elections brown replied 
that response reflected the dominant view in indianapolis to 
win elections the democrats must make clear to voters what they 
stand for 
it was with that in mind that brown also stepped up his attacks 
on the administrations record on the environment and education 
issues the president threatens to steal from the democrats 
bush convened the governors for an education summit last fall 
and rarely misses an opportunity to proclaim himself the 
education president 
he recently pleased environmentalists by endorsing legislation 
to upgrade the environmental protection agency to a cabinet 
department 
were not satisfied with sound bites and press conferences 
about education when children in eastern europe are outscoring 
american kids on standardized science exams and 60 million 
americans cant read at an eighthgrade level brown told the dnc 
he was equally scornful of the administration record on the 
environment he recalled the bush campaign commercials on pollution 
in boston harbor and chided the president for failing to clean it 
up 
party officials recognized the risk of endorsing strong action 
on social security 
i think its a little bit of a dangerous issue said jim 
ruvolo ohio democratic party chairman and president of the 
association of democratic state chairs 
ruvolo said the democrats must be careful not to allow the 
republicans to frame the debate as the democrats are threatening 
social security we know what kind of issue that is 
throughout the 1980s even at the height of ronald reagans 
popularity social security was an issue that won votes for the 
democrats because some elderly voters were convinced that reagan 
wanted to freeze benefits 
the cornerstone of the moynihan proposal is to say this fund 
ought to be sacrosanct said brown the proposal however has 
not received strong support from groups representing the elderly 
the democrats are hoping they can calm the fears of the elderly 
that moynihans plan would lead to a freeze or cutback in benefits 
at the same time the democrats are banking on the appeal of 
cutting the payroll tax which has risen steadily for several years 
brown had another weekend victory when he got his party to act 
quickly and quietly to set the rules for the 1992 campaign for the 
democratic presidential nomination 
this is the most peaceful accord on rules we have had in the 
past two decades he said with obvious satisfaction 
what made the democrats so willing to adopt their chairmans 
strategy 
the answer might lie in the underlying unease felt by many at 
the dnc meeting 
despite election successes in 1989 races democrats cant escape 
the reality of their national election losses 
we are not the majority party in this country said rep 
sander levin of michigan challenging a basic democratic tenet 
the party that loses five of six presidential elections is not 
the majority party 
</TEXT>
