<TEXT>
veteran northwest airlines pilot robert ralph 
johnson was so drunk leaving a racquet club that he fell on his way 
to his car a judge would later say it was amazing he could walk at 
all 
but the judge sealed police and court records to keep northwest 
and the federal aviation administration from learning of the case 
in exchange for a guilty plea to driving while intoxicated in july 
1988 
the reasons to save johnsons job and to get him into a 
treatment program johnson continued to fly for northwest as he 
had for almost 30 years the star tribune reported sunday 
the issue of pilot drunkenness gained new attention with the 
arrest march 8 of three other northwest airmen they were accused 
of drinking before a flight that day and of flying a plane with 91 
passengers aboard while intoxicated 
northwest fired captain norman prouse first officer robert 
kirchner and second officer joseph balzer who allegedly had 
bloodalcohol levels above 04 percent the legal limit for pilots 
officials said 
the star tribune said at least 41 pilots of passenger aircraft 
including 28 employed by northwest have lost their minnesota 
drivers licenses in the past seven years because of alcohol abuse 
in johnsons case if eaganbased northwest had learned of the 
incident he could have been grounded for at least two years under 
a strict alcohol policy that since has been relaxed 
if convicted of an alcoholrelated traffic offense johnson 
would have been required by the faa to report it on his medical 
exam raising the possibility that his fitness to fly would be 
examined 
but following johnsons guilty plea hennepin county district 
court judge david duffy decided not to accept it timothy ostroot 
johnsons lawyer told the associated press as part of the deal 
the judge ordered johnson to complete alcohol treatment and stay in 
contact with a probation officer 
if johnson upholds his part of the agreement the judge will 
dismiss the case in july without ever convicting johnson of drunken 
driving ostroot said 
northwest and faa officials declined to comment on the report 
as did a national spokesman for the air line pilots association 
eden prairie police had stopped johnson from driving his car out 
of the racquet clubs parking lot a breath test showed he had a 
33 percent bloodalcohol content 
nothing is to be disclosed to anybody regarding this duffy 
said during a hearing according to the newspaper and that would 
include the faa and that does not go on the driving record it 
goes nowhere but here 
when duffy asked what the faa could do johnson answered if 
it doesnt get out of this room they would never know 
duffy opened the file last week to a star tribune reporter who 
challenged the legality of sealing the records 
while johnson avoided faa scrutiny through that unusual court 
ruling other pilots do so in a more routine way the star tribune 
said 
in reviewing northwest pilots driving records the newspaper 
found seven cases in which alcoholrelated charges were reduced to 
nonalcohol offenses such as careless driving one was reduced to 
a charge of running a red light 
with alcohol removed from the convictions the pilots were under 
no obligation to tell the faa they were involved in a 
drunkendriving case thus avoiding evaluation of their alcohol use 
should such an evaluation show them to be alcoholic they could 
be suspended from flying until they could prove they could overcome 
alcoholism and abstained from drinking for two years the star 
tribune said 
duffy said last week he sealed johnsons records because it was 
the only way to get him to plead guilty and go into treatment 
without costing him his job 
under the old northwest policy duffy said if a pilot pled 
guilty to drunk driving he lost his job or if he went into 
treatment he lost his job under those circumstances nobody was 
going to plead guilty 
by this july if johnson has met the conditions set by the 
judge his case will be dismissed and his record will be clear 
since he was sentenced johnson has completed treatment and 
remained sober duffy said 
johnsons attorney timothy ostroot said duffys decision was 
proper under the circumstances 
this the drinking incident was completely unrelated to his 
job he said there was never any allegation he was going to 
fly the next day to me the price of losing his job which he 
worked very hard at and he was very good at for an alcoholrelated 
incident would be a heavy price to pay 
</TEXT>
