<TEXT>
six months after tropical storm hugos powerful 
winds cut a swath of destruction through north carolina the big 
threat now is forest fires 
mother nature lashed out against us not once but twice said 
state forester harry layman first we got the hurricane and now 
weve got to face the threat of forest fires 
layman estimated that hugo destroyed or damaged 27 million 
acres of trees worth about 250 million thats more timber than 
was destroyed by the mount st helens volcano the fires in 
yellowstone national park and hurricane camille combined he said 
as the springtime temperatures begin to rise tons of downed and 
shattered pines oaks hickorys and other trees continue to pile up 
and dry out on the floors of western north carolinas mountains 
its the worst fire threat the state has ever faced say layman 
and other experts authorities in south carolina also are concerned 
its real bad this year and its going to get worse in the 
second and third years layman said right now the twigs and 
branches are falling providing lots of kindling later the big 
trees are all going to be down its going to be a big bonfire 
any fire larger than five acres will soon be out of control 
and turn into a holocaust layman said 
charlotte was in the direct path of the eye of the storm after 
it came ashore 200 miles south near charleston sc in the 
predawn hours of sept 22 
while hugo was officially downgraded from a hurricane to a 
tropical storm just before it hit charlotte winds were clocked at 
90 mph and higher when the eye of the storm passed just over the 
western outskirts of the city 
piles of debris including tree stumps are still a common sight 
on some streets at some city parks youngsters play baseball and 
soccer games in open areas between large uprooted trees 
the city has carted away an estimated 100000 truckloads of hugo 
debris 
seven emergency landfills were opened to take the debris and 
four are already full 
were still getting 250 to 300 calls a day from people who 
want us to come to their homes and take away their debris said 
larry johnson assistant director of transportation whos in 
charge of the remaining cleanup 
back in the forests officials are preparing for a dry spring 
using a 33 million grant from the federal emergency managment 
administration 65 additional firefighters were hired abandoned 
fire towers were reactivated and new equipment including 
helicopters and bulldozers were brought in 
the state leased a tanker plane from the quebec government 
south carolina has leased two of the planes 
the north carolina forestry division has two planes combing the 
path of the storm looking for any signs of fire 
were working our hearts out to open up as many fire trails 
as we can layman said but we need 500 miles of trails in 
burke county alone and our crew can only do two miles a day 
the state may use prisoners to help clear paths into the forests 
that were blocked by downed trees 
timber companies are only able to clear about 7 percent of the 
damaged trees 
layman is considering imposing a strict burning ban beginning 
next month the worst time is april and may he said were 
hoping mother nature will cooperate but sooner or later were 
going to face it 
</TEXT>
