<TEXT>
if one state includes 5 million us citizens 
and another has 4 million citizens and 1 million illegal aliens 
which gets more seats in the house of representatives 
the answer they both get the same 
thats not fair say politicians from states that dont have 
many undocumented residents but thats what the constitution 
requires respond their counterparts in states with large numbers 
of them 
the dispute has provoked battles in federal court and congress 
as the census bureau prepares to go forth and count americans once 
again the national head count taken every 10 years got under way 
last week 
the results will be used to redistribute seats in the house in 
1992 and officials in states that have few illegal aliens fear 
losing political influence to states with many undocumented 
residents 
the number of house seats assigned to each state depends only on 
the total population of that state whether composed of citizens 
legal resident aliens or the undocumented 
the question is simple are people who have entered our 
country illegally entitled to representation in the united states 
congress i say no rep tom ridge rpa said recently in 
remarks echoed by rep tim valentine dnc and others 
rep william f goodling rpa contended that including 
illegal aliens gives undue influence to the citizens who live near 
them because noncitizens cannot vote it would take fewer 
citizens to elect a congressman in a district with a lot of aliens 
than in one with few goodling said 
ridge fought a losing battle in the house to require the census 
bureau to ask people if they are here legally and then to leave 
who arent out of the numbers used for apportionment 
a lawsuit filed by ridge and 41 other house members seeking the 
same result also was dismissed by a federal judge in pittsburgh 
despite the defeats he hasnt given up said aide mark 
campbell its too late to have changes made in the 1990 census 
but ridge is now aiming at the next count in the year 2000 
congress cannot by legislative action make persons into 
nonpersons for its political purposes rep esteban e torres 
dcalif argued for those who want an allinclusive count 
he stressed that while the constitution requires citizenship for 
certain public offices it specifically calls for the counting of 
all persons in the census 
a proposal to base house apportionment only on citizens was 
rejected a century ago when northern states included many new 
immigrants noted arturo vargas of the mexican american legal 
defense and education fund 
excluding undocumented residents from census counts would 
compel the census bureau to adopt untested techniques to 
determine the citizenship and immigration status of every person 
counted in the census vargas said 
this he said could have a chilling effect on the hispanic 
community discouraging participation of many legal residents 
trying to count legal and illegal residents separately will 
only lead to misrepresentation and inaccuracy both in the count 
numbers and in the reapportionment process said jaime b fuster 
puerto ricos resident commissioner in washington 
undersecretary of commerce michael r darby whose department 
includes the census bureau said we believe there are compelling 
legal and public policy grounds for counting all persons 
irrespective of their citizenship 
changing the policy of counting everyone would undermine efforts 
to get a complete census would discourage participation of 
minorities and could damage public perception of census 
confidentiality said darby 
in addition he said there is no effective way to know who is 
legal and who isnt of all the questions on the long and short 
forms none asks people if they reside in the country legally 
however estimates developed in 1985 indicated that excluding 
illegal aliens from the 1980 national head count would have 
affected two house seats 
thencensus director john g keane told a senate subcommittee 
that the bureau estimated that it had counted 2 million illegal 
residents in 1980 
had those people not been counted he said new york and 
california would each have lost one house seat with those seats 
going to georgia and indiana keane stressed however that his 
estimates were not accurate enough to use in actual 
reapportionments 
to the census bureau it doesnt really matter the constitution 
simply directs them to count all the people residing in the country 
a lot of illegal aliens will probably try to avoid the census 
anyway officials acknowledge wary of government efforts to return 
them to their homelands these people are often reluctant to deal 
with officials despite promises than any answers they give will be 
kept confidential 
</TEXT>
