<TEXT>
the agriculture department is amending federal 
regulations this week to allow the identification of swine shipped 
across state lines at the first point of concentration after 
leaving the farm 
james w glosser administrator of the departments animal and 
plant health inspection service said a final rule allowing the 
change will be published on tuesday 
previously he said hog producers were responsible in many 
cases for identifying swine before the animals moved into 
interstate commerce 
but the changes are necessary to provide for effective 
traceback of diseased or adulterated swine without unnecessarily 
disrupting standard marketing procedures glosser said 
federal rules requiring the interstate identification of swine 
took effect in november 1988 to help the agency locate hogs 
infected with disease an exception was made for hogs moving 
directly to slaughter plants from farrowtofinish operations 
the regulations define first points of concentration where 
identification may be performed 
for example glosser said that could include the point of first 
gathering or commingling of swine from more than one source such 
as a truck picking up hogs from different farms for delivery to 
market swine identified at this point could be traced directly 
back to herds of origin 
glosser said the rules also clarify the agencys list of 
approved devices used to identify swine in interstate commerce the 
devices used to identify hogs being shipped to slaughter plants 
include tattoos and usda backtags 
</TEXT>
