<TEXT>
a teenager who challenged the nations 
first law taking driving privileges from school dropouts becomes 
eligible to get his license back today but hell keep fighting the 
law 
the west virginia law which has been copied by a number of 
states including arkansas florida louisiana and texas suspends 
the drivers license of minors who continually cut class 
its effectiveness ends when the dropout turns 18 as michael 
means does today 
if i have to work monday ill work but one of the main 
things on the list is going to get the license means said as his 
birthday approached i think im just going to ride around the 
courthouse several hundred times 
means who does odd jobs to support his family expressed some 
remorse for leaving school early 
i know i lost something i can never regain but they think 
they can keep you in school by taking your license away and thats 
not very bright means said you cant train kids like you can 
dogs by taking something away 
the law was passed by the legislature in 1988 to help curb the 
states 17 percent dropout rate it revokes students licenses 
until they are 18 if they miss more than 10 consecutive days of 
school or have more than 15 unexcused absences 
means a married father who gave up on a formal education at age 
16 was among the first to become entangled in the law after he 
lost his license and applied for a new one 
the department of motor vehicles citing the dropout law 
refused to issue another license without the consent of the kanawha 
county board of education and the school board rejected means 
hardship argument that he was unable to support his family without 
driving 
means took the officials to court but he lost in circuit court 
in august he has appealed to the state supreme court which is 
likely to hear the case in september 
means attorney chris butch argues it is illogical to take a 
shotgun approach to force teenagers to return to school while 
at the same allowing them to drop out at age 16 butch also argued 
the policy is discriminatory because rural youths unlike city 
dwellers lack access to public transportation means lives on the 
outskirts of charleston 
despite the controversy education officials say the law has 
helped trim the dropout rate to 16 percent 
its not the answer its another strategy were using to help 
deal with the dropout program said therese wilson of the state 
department of education 
if we look at the number of kids who came back because of the 
law when over 300 come back thats 300 kids we would not have 
gotten if it had not been for the law she said 
the law resulted in 687 suspensions for the 198889 school year 
said tom madden general counsel for the motor vehicle division by 
the end of the year nearly 250 of those teenagers had their 
licenses reinstated by returning to school or enrolling in a high 
school equivalency degree program hardship exemptions were given 
to 43 and 157 dropouts got their licenses back when they turned 18 
madden said 376 suspensions have been issued during the current 
school year and 74 young people got their licenses back by 
returning to school or enrolling in an equivalencydegree program 
means who lives in his parents home with his 17yearold wife 
also a dropout and his 7monthold son said he would continue his 
fight even though he now is old enough to get a license 
i guess the only thing i really want is my license back but i 
just want to give other people a chance that dont have one he 
said 
