<TEXT>
the trial of an aidsinfected inmate accused 
of trying to spread the deadly disease by biting a guard marks a 
disturbing trend in criminal justice according to some aids 
litigation experts 
jury selection was to begin today in superior court in the case 
of gregory smith 26 who faces an attempted murder charge 
theres never been a case of hiv being transmitted through a 
bite or saliva said larry gostin executive director of the 
american society of law and medicine which recently completed a 
nationwide aids litigation project for the us public health 
service 
as a result its not a realistic attempted murder charge 
he said 
gostin and others fear smiths case will fuel hysterical fears 
of acquired immune deficiency syndrome 
smith is one of 10 prisoners around the country charged last 
year with trying to kill or injure law enforcement officers by 
infecting them with aids according to judy greenspan information 
director for the american civil liberties unions national prison 
project in washington dc 
most unfortunately this is an alarming trend in the criminal 
justice system said ms greenspan who tracks aidsrelated cases 
for the aclu 
the whole fact that prisoners who are hivinfected are being 
treated differently in the courts is a very serious problem 
aids an affliction that attacks the bodys immune system is 
most often transmitted through sexual contact and among people who 
share needles while abusing drugs its spread in this country began 
among gay men 
it also can be transmitted through transfusions of blood or 
blood products medical experts say it is unlikely that the virus 
can be transmitted by biting 
smith was indicted last summer by a county grand jury on 
attempted murder charges after he allegedly bit a guard three times 
on the hand on june 11 the guard was trying to put smith into a 
patrol car to transport him back to the jail after he underwent 
treatment for a back injury at cooper medical center 
smith who was serving a fiveyear sentence for a robbery 
conviction allegedly yelled now die you pig prosecutors 
said 
the officer was not wearing protective gear or gloves although 
smith was known to have tested positive for the aids virus 
smith has denied biting the guard shortly after the incident 
he was transferred to trenton state prison 
assistant camden county prosecutor harold kasselman who is 
handling the case declined to be interviewed last week citing 
concern over pretrial publicity smiths attorney did not return 
telephone calls seeking comment 
over 100 lawsuits have been filed against aidsinfected 
individuals charging them with attempting to spread the disease 
through biting spitting throwing feces or splattering blood 
according to gostin 
other cases include 
an infected minnesota inmate was convicted of assault with a 
deadly weapon after biting a guard a federal appeals court upheld 
the conviction 
a centre county pa inmate was convicted of assault after 
throwing feces on a state prison guard the conviction has been 
appealed 
an attempted suicide victim in indiana who threw blood at 
emergency personnel was convicted of three counts of attempted 
murder and sentenced to 120 years imprisonment the verdict was set 
aside by the trial judge but reinstated at the appellate level 
the case is pending before the indiana supreme court 
in some ways its almost akin to sticking a pin in a voodoo 
doll and hoping that someone will die said gostin an associate 
professor at harvards school of public health prosecution of the 
inmates constitutes pretty much a a travesty of the legal 
system he said 
