<TEXT>
the first american novel known to be 
written by a black person described racism in the north just before 
the civil war an unwelcome message that may have helped keep the 
1859 book obscure researchers said 
i think its the kind of statement that white new hampshire 
resents in 1990 said barbara white an associate professor of 
womens studies at the university of new hampshire think of what 
people would have thought in 1859 
harriet e wilsons our nig also depicts hypocrisy among 
white abolitionists and for the first time in american literature 
a successful interracial marriage 
the book was published again in 1983 and more recently has 
attracted attention from researchers like white who are trying to 
find out more about the author white plans to make her research 
public sometime this summer 
published in boston under a pseudonym identical to the title 
the books lengthy subtitle doesnt mince words sketches from 
the life of a free black in a twostory white house north 
showing that slaverys shadows fall even there 
the title itself undoubtedly ruffled feathers at the time white 
said 
people who ordinarily wouldve been sympathetic to a black 
woman writing a narrative werent going to be sympathetic to 
that she said 
cornell university professor henry louis gates has written that 
wilson dared to entitle her text with the most feared and hated 
epithet by which the very humanity of black people had been 
demeaned 
gates discovered an original edition of our nig in a 
manhattan book store when he was a graduate student he traced it 
to wilson with the help of several locals including amherst 
librarian erna johnson and milford town clerks nancy schooley and 
helen draper 
milford where wilson lived in the 1840s was known to have had 
an active abolitionist community gates said our nig not only 
would have offended whites but also blacks who feared it would 
hurt the antislavery movement 
that such a significant novel the very first written by a 
black woman would remain unnoticed in boston in 1859 a veritable 
center of abolitionist reform and passion and by a growing black 
press eager to celebrate all black achievement in the arts and 
sciences remains one of the troubling enigmas of afroamerican 
literary history gates wrote 
but melvin dixon a professor of afroamerican literature at 
queens college in new york said he believes the relative obscurity 
of black authors in general not the books views played a major 
role in keeping the book little known 
white readers were not taking seriously the writing of 
afroamerican scholars dixon said 
white said she is still establishing basic facts about wilson 
like her birth and death dates she also is trying to determine 
whether a real family was the white family depicted in our nig 
our nig is the story of frado daughter of a white woman and 
a black man raised as a servant by a white family in the 
fictitious community of singleton nh 
abandoned by her impoverished mother at a young age frado grows 
up working for the bellmont family and suffering verbal abuse and 
beatings at mrs bellmonts hands 
wilson wrote that frado was maltreated by professed 
abolitionists who didnt want slaves in the south nor niggers in 
their own houses north and could not bear to lodge one to eat 
with one to admit one through the front door to sit next one 
awful 
later frado all but abandons her faith and decides that if 
mrs bellmont is going to heaven shed rather go to hell 
elsewhere frado asks the kindly james bellmont who made me 
so james answers god 
who made your mother frado persists 
god 
did the same god that made her make me 
yes 
well then i dont like him 
why not 
because he made her white and me black why didnt he make us 
both white 
</TEXT>
