<TEXT>
gay activists claimed victory after an 
international exhibit about the holocaust opened with references to 
homosexual victims of nazi persecution that some utah education 
officials had wanted removed 
about 200 homosexuals and civil libertarians rallied outside the 
exhibit sunday then walked to a nearby episcopal cathedral for a 
holocaust memorial many wore on their lapels the pink triangle 
which the nazis used to tag homosexuals and the gay rights movement 
has appropriated as its symbol 
no one is allowed to rewrite history said robert austin 
who said he represented a looseknit coalition of utah gay and 
human rights organizations i want you to know that not one word 
has been deleted we won 
utah office of education officials earlier this month told 
orembased geneva steel co the corporate sponsor of the world 
of anne frank 19281945 that references to homosexual holocaust 
victims in materials given to teachers and guides might violate a 
state law prohibiting promotion of homosexuality in schools 
the company in turn deleted two pages dealing with the 
treatment of homosexuals after adolf hitlers rise to power in 
1933 thousands of homosexuals were rounded up and sent to 
concentration camps where they were often castrated exterminated 
or worked to death 
a third page showed the pink triangle surrounded by the words 
gays against facism and a brief history of how the symbol was 
adopted by the gay liberation movement in the 1970s 
school officials worried the reference might be construed as 
promulgating homosexuality and asked that it be removed 
protests from homosexuals utahs jewish community and others 
resulted in the materials being restored school board and geneva 
officials called the incident a misunderstanding 
the exhibit contains more than 600 photographs depicting the 
life and times of the young jewish girl whose diaries have been 
read by millions since she perished in a concentration camp in 1945 
only a single caption refers to the persecution of homosexuals 
under nazi rule officials said nobody wanted that reference 
removed 
cornelius suijk international director of the anne frank 
exhibit said he found the incident unfortunate but understood 
how it occurred 
you have to remember that it took 20 years before homosexuals 
in holland were allowed to take part in the annual holocaust 
remembrance he said but they were victims of hitler and 
should be memorialized 
suijk who was accompanying the exhibit throughout its 38city 
tour said geneva officials have made every effort to maintain the 
exhibits integrity 
the exhibit opened at noon sunday at the citycounty building 
and in the evening homosexuals and others held a ceremony to honor 
homosexual holocaust victims outside 
michele a parishpixler executive director of the utah chapter 
of the american civil liberties union congratulated utah 
homosexuals for risking their anonymity and in some cases their 
livelihoods in protesting the deletions 
if the fear is not allowed to grow we wont find ourselves 
being hauled off to concentration camps she said we cannot 
let past oppressions be smothered under a blanket of silence 
the gathering marched to the nearby episcopal cathedral church 
of st mark for a holocaust memorial where bishop michael coburn 
asked for prayers not just for those who died in the death camps 
but for victims of discrimination worldwide 
geneva president joseph a cannon who was critical of the 
deletions when he learned of them said prior to the opening of the 
exhibit that his company was committed to an accurate portrayal of 
history including the nazi persecution of homosexuals 
all in all its been a good experience he said basically 
im just president of a steel company but ive had a lot of nice 
letters from the gay community 
