<TEXT>
the supreme court today agreed to consider 
giving federal regulators more authority to lower electricity 
rates setting the stage for a decision that could affect more than 
49 million homes 
the court said it will review a ruling that barred the federal 
energy regulatory commission from slashing rate increases to 
customers in 15 ohio communities 
a decision is expected sometime in 1991 
at stake is the commissions power to prevent public utilities 
from passing on to consumers allegedly inflated costs of buying 
coal and possibly other goods and services from utility 
subsidiaries 
the bush administration joined the ohio communities in urging 
the court to study the case 
the dispute stems from rate hikes first proposed by ohio power 
co in 1982 the utility asked the commission to approve higher 
rates to cover the cost of buying coal from its subsidiary the 
southern ohio coal co 
the commission concluded that ohio power from 1982 to 1986 paid 
its subsidiary between 25 percent and 33 percent more for coal than 
the prevailing market prices 
the commission ordered the utility to refund 134 million to 
its wholesale customers for that period 
but a us circuit court of appeals here which has authority 
over such actions by federal regulators overturned the 
commissions decision last year 
the appeals court interpreted a 1935 federal law to give the 
securities and exchange commission primary authority to regulate 
sales contracts between holding companies and their subsidiaries 
the sec is charged by the statute with regulating the terms of 
affiliate contracts in the interest of consumers as well as 
investors and the public and has not exempted the contract 
between ohio power and the southern ohio coal co the appeals 
court said 
justice department lawyers said the ruling creates the 
potential for a serious regulatory gap with respect to federal and 
by implication state regulation of utility rates 
the decision could hinder effective regulation of utilities 
that directly or indirectly serve 49 million households 
nationwide the goverment said 
