the supreme court today rejected an appeal by 
a major conglomerate found to have fraudulently obtained a 75 
million bank loan to develop natural gas fields in mississippi 
the court without comment left intact a ruling that could 
subject wr grace amp co to substantial punitive damages in a 
lawsuit by the federal deposit insurance corp 
continental illinois national bank made the loan to grace in 
1980 to finance the companys acquisition of three mississippi gas 
fields 
grace discovered before the loan was approved that one of the 
fields apparently was worthless but it did not reveal that 
development to the bank for three years 
the bank then sued the conglomerate for fraud in 1984 the bank 
soon assigned the grace loan to the fdic since the government 
agency was helping bail out the failing bank 
a federal jury awarded the fdic 100 million in damages 
including 25 million to compensate the agency for its losses and 
75 million to punish grace a federal judge reduced the 75 
milllion portion of the award to 25 million 
the 7th us circuit court of appeals last year upheld the 
jurys finding of fraud but ordered a new trial on damages 
the appeals court said there was sufficient evidence the company 
practiced fraud to obtain the loan concealment was the essence 
of graces fraud the appeals court said only after grace 
thought it was home free in fact three years after it thought it 
was home free did it reveal the fraud 
but the 7th circuit court said it was troubled by the way the 
jury decided the fdic suffered 25 million in actual damages 
the jury was allowed to pick a figure out of the air the 
appeals court said the amount of punitive damages related as 
they are to compensatory damages will have to be redetermined as 
well in the new trial 
graces lawyers urged the supreme court to use the case to 
decide whether a government agency may be awarded punitive damages 
in fraud lawsuits 
the grace appeal also said it is unfair to limit the new trial 
ordered by the appeals court to the size of damages 
justice department lawyers in asking the high court to reject 
graces appeal said it borders on brazenness for the 
conglomerate to argue that the fdic is not entitled to major 
damages when grace has failed to repay a 75 million loan 
the case is wr grace vs fdic 89902 
