<TEXT>
an evansville ind business convicted and 
fined 5000 for showing and selling movies harmful to minors 
lost a supreme court appeal today 
the court without comment refused to hear arguments that the 
conviction and fine infringe the freespeech rights of the studio 
art theatres owners and violate the required separation of 
government and religion 
the business was indicted in 1986 on charges of violating the 
indiana criminal racketeer influenced and corrupt organizations act 
rico by selling and displaying movies in violation of state law 
the underlying state law bars a business from selling or 
displaying materials that are deemed harmful to minors within 500 
feet of the nearest property line of any church or school 
the studio art theatre is located within 500 feet of a church 
at a nonjury trial lawyers for the business agreed to let four 
sexually explicit movies be considered harmful for children under 
18 but noted it was never alleged that any youngster actually saw 
or bought those movies there 
a state judge found the studio art theatre guilty of the rico 
violations and a state appeals court upheld the conviction in 1988 
without addressing the constitutional challenge raised 
the appeal acted on today attacked the 500foot law saying it 
violates freespeech rights because the offending materials do not 
even have to be judged obscene and therefore unworthy of 
constitutional protection 
the appeal also said the studio art theatre owners right to be 
fair treatment under equalprotection guarantees is violated 
because exceptions to the 500foot ban are made for materials 
available at certain libraries museums and schools 
and the appeal said the challenged law impermissibly delegates 
to a church the ability to criminalize conduct that otherwise was 
constitutionally protected simply because it locates within 500 
feet 
lawyers for the studio art theatre said the law has the 
constitutionally impermissible effect of advancing or promoting 
religion 
the justices last year used an indiana case to rule that states 
may use antiracketeering laws to crack down on adult bookstores 
and other sexually oriented businesses 
but the court said in that decision that prosecutors may not use 
state rico laws to close down such businesses before trials are 
held to determine whether any of the material displayed or sold is 
obscene 
the case acted on today is studio art theatre vs indiana 
89847 
</TEXT>
