<TEXT>
the supreme court today agreed to hear an 
appeal challenging the authority of states to house convicted 
murderers on death rows and keep them apart from other inmates 
the justices said they will review the appeal of nebraska death 
row inmate john rust who says such segregation is without 
penological justification and grossly disproportionate 
punishment 
rusts unusual appeal which he authored himself does not 
challenge his death sentence but only the conditions of his death 
row confinement 
the appeal in essence says segregating inmates who are to be 
executed violates their dueprocess and equalprotection rights 
rust was convicted of murder and sentenced to death in 1975 
from the time of his imprisonment until 1978 he was allowed to 
remain with inmates who were serving prison terms but were not 
under death sentences 
but in 1978 nebraska chose to segregate all inmates under death 
sentences on one death row at the nebraska state penitentiary a 
kind of administrative segregation 
most states with death penalty laws also feature a death row 
where inmates under death sentences are kept removed from other 
inmates 
death row inmates generally do not have all the privileges of 
other prison inmates 
rust was convicted of killing michael kellogg who had come to 
the aid of police officers during a supermarket robbery in omaha 
rust is the longestserving death row inmate in a state that has 
not executed anyone for three decades 
his appeal also argued that switching the conditions of his 
confinement in 1978 represented a constitutionally impermissible 
ex post facto punishment 
the case is rust vs gunter 895900 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

