<TEXT>
fustian house in wiltshire is the dullest 
stately home in england nothing interesting has happened there for 
the last 400 years so what is a poor tour guide to do 
make up an interesting history for the old place says lettice 
douffet a lady as eccentric and exotic as her first and last 
names her embellishments set in motion lettice and lovage 
peter shaffers enormously entertaining comedy about the unlikely 
friendship between two very different women 
and when the women are played by such accomplished actresses as 
maggie smith as the overimaginative tour guide and margaret 
tyzack as her frustrated boss it makes for a very merry evening 
indeed 
lettice and lovage a big london hit opened sunday night at 
broadways ethel barrymore theater where the play should run for 
as long as smith wants to do it the comedy directed with a sure 
steady hand by michael blakemore is what used to be a called a 
star turn a chance for theatergoers to see an actor or actress 
do what they do best 
and shaffer author of such diverse and weightier plays as 
equus and amadeus certainly gives smith a lot of 
opportunities the play opens with several hilarious short scenes 
as lettice describes the history of fustian house in increasingly 
inaccurate detail to a group of gullible tourists 
smith her hair a striking mop of red curls doesnt just recite 
this bogus history she sweeps into it arms flailing like a dying 
swan her voice a mixture of murmurs coos and trills earns 
applause from her enthusiastic pupils and the audience 
unfortunately one member of the tour turns out to be lotte schoen 
her supervisor who then fires the woman for falsifying history 
for much of the play shaffer contrasts the two middleaged 
spinsters and their different philosophies of life enlarge 
enliven enlighten exhorts lettice who learned the three words 
from her mother a free spirit who performed shakespeares plays in 
french her own translations lettice proudly announces 
lotte is a bitter woman unhappy about her life but she feels 
sorry for lettice and tries to get her another job this time as a 
tour guide on a boat traveling the thames gradually their 
friendship builds 
their love for the england and particularly london of 
yesterday is what unites them they lament the destruction of great 
old buildings and castigate the modern monstrosities that have gone 
up in their place 
the plot falters a bit at the end of the second act and its 
odd that one of the plays major events occurs off stage between 
the second and third acts everyone talks about the incident 
particularly a lawyer crisply played by the wonderful paxton 
whitehead 
tyzack is a worthy foil for the extravagant smith bette 
henritze scores as lottes dithering secretary and there is a 
scenestealing bit by a large blinking gray cat christened by 
lettice with typical theatricality as felina queen of sorrows 
but theres no doubt that lettice and lovage really belongs 
to smith and she revels in its glorious excesses its a perfect 
marriage of star and story 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
what other critics said 
frank rich the new york times this is idiosyncratic theater 
acting of a high and endangered order not to be confused with the 
actress tightly minimalistic film work if lettice and lovage 
is but a modest excuse for it what theater lover needs any excuse 
whatsoever to have a rare reunion with maggie smith 
howard kissel the daily news at heart the play is a 
celebration of the imagination a celebration of the art of 
theater with these celebrants theres great cause for rejoicing 
clive barnes new york post this is no mere onewoman triumph 
playwright peter shaffer and his director michael blakemore have 
conspired with actresses the ebulliently bewitching smith and a 
queen of more stately necromancy margaret tyzack to produce an 
evening of enchantment and delight 
