<TEXT>
the supreme court today agreed to decide 
whether railroads can ignore union contracts to complete mergers 
approved by the interstate commerce commission 
the court said it will review a ruling that restrains the 
railroads and the icc from overriding collective bargaining 
agreements 
the us circuit court of appeals here ruled for the unions last 
july in two separate cases 
the first case stems from icc approval in 1980 of acquisition by 
csx corp of the chessie system and seaboard coast line industries 
cxs decided in 1986 to close its freight car repair shop at 
waycross ga and to transfer work done there to a chessie system 
shop in raceland ky 
the transfer meant eliminating jobs and transferring some 
waycross workers to raceland transferred workers were told they no 
longer could count on lifetime income guaranteed by the contract 
signed by csx and the brotherhood of railway carmen 
in the second case norfolk and western railway co and the 
southern railway co announced in 1986 plans to merge operations 
centers in roanoke va and atlanta the consolidation eliminated 
some supervisors jobs at roanoke 
the american train dispatchers association said the plans 
violated the unions contract with norfolk and western 
the icc in both cases said the railroads were exempt from the 
union contracts 
but the appeals court here said congress has not given the icc 
such broad power with so much potential to destablize the 
railroad industry 
we can not impute to congress the intention to make the 
bargainedfor provisions of a collective bargaining agreement 
contingent upon their not later becoming inconvenient to the full 
realization of operating economies that a merger might make 
possible the appeals court said 
it ordered further review by the icc in both cases 
the bush administration urged the supreme court not to disturb 
the appeals court ruling 
the cases are norfolk and western vs american train 
dispatchers 891027 csx transportation vs brotherhood of railway 
carmen 891928 
