<TEXT>
the trial of imelda marcos in new 
york has spared the manila government a political dilemma but it 
also has raised questions about whether she should have been 
prosecuted first on foreign soil 
mrs marcos widow of former president ferdinand marcos went on 
trial last week in a manhattan federal court on racketeering 
charges in connection with the alleged looting of the philippine 
treasury during her husbands 20year rule 
president corazon aquinos administration claims marcos his 
family and associates embezzled up to 10 billion before he was 
ousted four years ago 
despite the allegations neither marcos nor his widow was ever 
charged in the philippines with a criminal offense although they 
have been named in more than 30 civil suits 
the philippine constitution forbids trials in absentia and 
officials feared the marcoses would invoke their right to return 
from exile if criminal charges were filed marcos died in hawaii in 
september 
the absence of criminal charges has impeded efforts to recover 
the fortune marcos allegedly transferred abroad authorities in 
switzerland where much of the wealth is believed deposited 
stalled on lifting banking secrecy laws pending criminal charges 
officials hope that a conviction by an american court will speed 
the transfer of marcos assets it would also make it unlikely that 
mrs marcos could return to the philippines before mrs aquinos 
term expires in 1992 
when the trial began many filipino commentators expressed 
satisfaction that mrs marcos would finally have to answer in court 
to allegations of profligacy and corruption 
even though the opening days have been devoted to the mundane 
problems of jury selection the trial has been frontpage news in 
the philippines 
she went on fabulous shopping sprees and gave lavish 
parties wrote the manila standard now she faces charges 
which suggest that these were made possible in large part by the 
money she has embezzled 
others however questioned the wisdom of allowing the americans 
the former colonial power to determine her guilt or innocence 
the united states had the right to do so because the alleged 
offenses violated us law 
this means the loss of the nations supreme legal authority to 
