<TEXT>
klaus e knorr professor emeritus of 
public affairs at princeton university and a former director of its 
center of international studies has died of cancer he was 78 
the germanborn economist and political scientist died at his 
home sunday 
in his writings knorr argued against use of military force 
during the nuclear age 
during the buildup of us military involvement in vietnam in 
1968 knorr called for the withdrawal of american and north 
vietnamese forces introduction of an international peacekeeping 
force and the formation of a neutral government in south vietnam 
the war continued for seven more years 
knorr earned his law degree in germany and left for the united 
states in 1937 after resisting pressure to join the nazi party 
he earned a phd at the university of chicago in 1941 and 
taught economics at stanford yale and princeton where he remained 
for 28 years he directed princetons center of international 
studies from 1960 to 1968 
his works included on the uses of military power in the 
nuclear age military power and potential and power and 
wealth the political economy of international power 
survivors include his wife marianne daughters monica of 
washington and jean of alexandria va and son nicholas of 
glencoe ill 
</TEXT>
