<TEXT>
soybean products may help prevent 
breast cancer and a new laboratory test may enable doctors to 
better choose therapy for breast cancer patients according to two 
preliminary studies released monday 
rats fed a soybeancontaining diet showed lower breastcancer 
rates in a laboratory experiment said stephen barnes an associate 
professor of pharmacology and biochemistry at the university of 
alabama at birmingham 
he tried the experiment after noting that soybeans are prominent 
in diets of asian countries that have lower breastcancer rates 
than the united states he said 
but he stressed that his work only studied rats and his 
hypothesis is not ready for experiments in people 
dont get too excited yet barnes told science writers at a 
seminar sponsored by the american cancer society 
i think what weve got here is a possibility that needs to be 
pursued people shouldnt be encouraged to rush into this 
samuel broder director of the national cancer institute said 
he found the soybean idea fascinating but agreed that it is 
not clear whether it applies to people 
this is just a hypothesis he said please do not write 
headlines that soybeans are good for preventing breast cancer 
he also cautioned that many factors other than soybeans could 
explain the low breastcancer rates in asian countries 
in barnes study 300 rats animals were fed diets in which 
amounts of total protein and carbohydrates were kept constant but 
the amount of soybean protein and carbohydrates varied 
after the animals ate the diets for four weeks they were given 
a cancercausing substance tumors began to show up after another 
four weeks or so 
animals that ate soybean diets showed only about half as many 
tumors on average as those on the soybeanfree diet barnes said 
barnes said his work was financed largely by the cancer society 
with no funding from soybean companies 
he said it is not clear what component of soybeans may suppress 
breast cancer but he said molecules of one component called 
isoflavones bear a structural resemblance to tamoxifen a 
substance used in treating some breastcancer patients 
tamoxifen works by blocking a cancer cells ability to absorb 
and use estrogen which some cells use to fuel growth perhaps 
isoflavones do the same thing thus suppressing breast cancer he 
said 
the other study presented also dealt with the use of estrogen by 
breastcancer cells 
cells take up estrogen by snaring it with proteins on cell 
surfaces called estrogen receptors doctors routinely check 
breastcancer tumors to see if they have these receptors if they 
do doctors prescribe an estrogenblocking agent such as tamoxifen 
to be used after surgery 
if the breastcancer tumors do not show estrogen receptors 
doctors prescribe chemotherapy instead as a followup to surgery 
however a woman whose tumor contains estrogen receptors may 
have only a 40 percent to 80 percent chance of being helped by 
antiestrogen therapy said christopher benz of the university of 
california san francisco 
other tests can identify women with higher chances of 
responding but most community doctors decide on therapy after just 
checking for presence of the estrogen receptor benz said 
his study suggests that a new lab test may be able to identify 
women who have estrogen receptors but who would not respond to 
antiestrogen therapy 
the problem with the current test is that it fails to determine 
whether the estrogen receptors it finds will work normally he 
said receptors are supposed to bind to a cells genetic material 
after they snare estrogen 
in a study of 40 human tumors that had estrogen receptors benz 
found that 40 percent contained only abnormal receptors that failed 
to bind to genetic material 
such tumors might behave as if they lacked the receptors 
altogether and so not respond to antiestrogen therapy benz said 
to test that idea the women from whom the tumors were taken 
will have to be followed for several years he said if it turns 
out to be true the new test might help doctors make better 
decisions about what kind of therapy to prescribe after surgery he 
said 
broder said the work raises an exciting question for future 
research and that we have to keep an open mind on whether the 
test would be useful in treatment decisions 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

