bank town of bethlehem and the neighboring villages of beit jala 
and beit sahour 
slogans on walls signed by the popular front and the 
fundamentalist islamic jihad group called for burying the camp 
david accords the accords led to the israelegypt peace treaty 
signed march 26 1979 
past disputes on goals and tactics already have splintered the 
uprising leadership 
the moslem fundamentalist movement hamas which rejects any 
compromise with israel has for more than a year set its own strike 
agenda it often is at odds with the main underground coalitions 
schedule of strikes 
the other factions largely have acted together since a 
fivepoint pact last july pledged cooperation and ended a rash of 
torchings of rivals cars 
the latest rift was sparked by the decision of the united 
leadership to allow merchants to open their stores for five hours a 
day starting march 20 earlier merchants were restricted to a 
threehour work day 
the popular front in its leaflets said the longer hours were a 
sign of weakness they said palestinians should increase civil 
disobedience by lengthening strikes intensifying the boycott of 
israelimade goods staging larger demonstrations and throwing more 
firebombs 
