american continental corp of phoenix to make the 14186000 
payment a month earlier than it was due 
government lawyer james murphy said the memo bolsters 
regulators contention that lincoln was using complicated real 
estate stock and junk bond transactions to book phony profits to 
bolster keatings faltering real estate empire 
in its april takeover of the thrift the government contended 
that american continental looted lincoln of 94 million through the 
taxsharing arrangement under the agreement the holding company 
collected taxes due on the phony profits but never paid them to the 
irs the government contends 
although an outline of the taxsharing arrangement had been 
approved by regulators on the west coast government attorneys 
contend it was illegal 
meanwhile andre niebling lincolns chairman from mid1985 
through mid1987 has refused to testify citing a fifth amendment 
protection against selfincrimination 
niebling said in an affidavit that a federal grand jury in los 
angeles is weighing possible criminal charges against keating and 
other american continental and lincoln officials 
mark sauter lincolns general counsel refused earlier to 
testify 
government lawyers alleged monday that during a july 1986 
meeting with federal regulators keating cited an upcoming meeting 
with rep john dingell dmich the powerful chairman of the house 
energy and commerce committee 
keatings top aide american continental president judith 
wischer testified that she could not recall keating making that 
remark or referring to dingell 
keating would not comment to reporters on what he said at the 
meeting he said he did meet with dingel later to voice complaints 
about regulators but did not discuss lincolns particular problems 
keating said he had met with about 50 members of congress since 
1984 to complain about the way thenchairmen edwin gray and grays 
successor m danny wall were running the federal home loan bank 
board the thrift industrys chief regulator 
dennis fitzgibbons a spokesman for dingell confirmed that 
dingell and keating met in late july 1986 
he keating wanted dingell to go after gray and dingell 
refused fitzgibbons said 
the senate ethics committee is investigating five senators 
intervention with bank board officials in 1987 on lincolns behalf 
the senators who together received 13 million in political funds 
from keating have denied any ethics violations 
they are alan cranston dcalif dennis deconcini dariz 
john mccain rariz john glenn dohio and donald w riegle jr 
dmich 
