<TEXT>
the agriculture department is proposing a 
federal milk marketing order to include north carolina and south 
carolina officials said monday 
daniel d haley administrator of the departments agricultural 
marketing service said the recommendation was based on hearings 
held last year he said order would require the approval of milk 
producers before it could take effect 
haley said the marketing order which would set minimum prices 
bottlers would have to pay dairy farmers for their milk is 
necessary to ensure an adequate supply of milk for consumers in the 
two states 
the primary milk consumption areas include charlotte 
greensboro winstonsalem raleigh durham asheville and 
fayetteville in north carolina and columbia charleston and 
greenville in south carolina 
haley said the federal marketing order would resolve milk supply 
problems in these states north carolina regulates its milk 
production under a state marketing order and south carolina has no 
milk marketing regulations he said 
a federal order will match supply and demand for the entire 
area with special circumstances spelled out to deal with the uses 
of milk in oversupply and to encourage delivery of milk to 
bottling plants in undersupply haley said 
federal milk marketing orders do not set retail prices paid by 
consumers for milk he said however the orders do affect 
consumers by assuring a balance between supply and demand for milk 
