<TEXT>
cigarette prices would rise to 5 a 
pack tobacco advertising would be banned and minors would be 
barred from buying cigarettes under a proposal submitted to the 
government monday 
everyone should have the right to a smokefree environment said 
an accompanying report the first government study on smoking since 
1973 
its recommendations would give sweden along with norway and 
finland one of the worlds toughest antismoking laws 
the swedish tobacco industry said it would suffer from an 
advertising ban and lose out to foreign brands 
a bunch of wellpaid tobaccohating bureaucrats spent a year 
on nice trips and came up with nothing sensible klaus unger 
chairman of swedish tobacco co was quoted as saying by the 
expressen newspaper 
smokepeace a lobby against laws that would further limit 
smokers rights said the recommendations would give hardpressed 
supermarket cashiers the duties of policemen 
some of the proposals already adopted by other countries 
proved ineffective in stopping youngsters from smoking the lobby 
said 
the report submitted to social affairs minister ingela thalen 
is the first stage of the legislative process that could take 
several months it must be submitted for comment to various 
interested parties including the tobacco industry and may undergo 
major revisions before it becomes law 
the report recommended a 15milligram limit on tar in 
cigarettes that would effectively ban 36 popular brands now on 
sale in sweden including 26 imported brands finland already has a 
similar ban and the report said the european community will adopt 
the limit in 1993 
roland perlstrom speaking for the industry said the proposal 
was unnecessary because smokers are switching to lowtar 
cigarettes which already have 60 percent of the market 
under the proposal cigarette prices would rise 50 percent to 5 
hotels would be required to forbid smoking in half their rooms 
and restaurants with more than 50 seats would have to have 
nonsmoking areas at work places smoking would be allowed in 
designated areas or in offices only if the smoke did not spread to 
smokefree zones 
after what we know about the damaging effects of tobacco the 
use of tobacco cannot be regarded and treated as a harmless habit 
or a private matter any more the report said 
</TEXT>
