<TEXT>
the pilot of avianca flight 52 was aware 
that he was low on gas but appeared inattentive to the problem 
and seemed to take little action in communicating it to air 
controllers a source told the associated press monday 
the flights copilot and flight engineer also took no bold 
steps to alert the captain or controllers to the fuel emergency a 
source close to the investigation said he spoke on the condition 
of anonymity 
the findings were based on conversations recorded in the cockpit 
of the colombian flight during the 30 minutes before it crashed 
into a hillside in cove neck long island jan 25 killing 73 of 
the 159 aboard 
the transcripts which were to be released tuesday by the 
national transportation safety board indicated that the lack of 
communication among the cockpit crew contributed to the crash 
the boeing 707 from bogota and medellin colombia crashed in 
fog and rain on final approach just northeast of john f kennedy 
international airport 
investigators believe the plane crashed because it ran out of 
fuel 
they are not certain why the crew members failed to make it 
clear to air traffic controllers how urgent their fuel shortage had 
become 
the recorded conversations indicate that the crew mostly in 
spanish discussed the dwindling fuel supply among themselves 
the transcripts appear to show a pilot who did not seem to be in 
full charge of the situation the source said and who did not give 
specific essential direction to the copilot to declare an 
emergency 
they also showed a copilot who had just 2 years of experience 
flying into jfk and appeared reluctant to assert himself the 
source said 
the flight engineer had several years experience but also 
seemed to be hesitant to speak up although he appeared to be 
subtly trying to remind the pilot of the fuel shortage the source 
said 
all three crew members died in the crash 
after aborting his first approach the captain a 17year 
veteran pilot asked the copilot if he had told air traffic 
controllers that they had an emergency 
the copilot who handled most of the communications with 
controllers did answered i told them were low on fuel 
the captain according to the transcripts did not respond to 
the copilot nor did he followup by instructing the copilot to 
tell air traffic control that they had an emergency 
after the aborted approach the crew accepted without 
challenge a new route for a second approach that looped over the 
long island sound 
at that point investigators have said the pilot and crew made 
a deadly mistake 
they should have made it clear to controllers that they needed 
to come straight in for a landing even a straight in landing 
where the plane would have needed to make a tight loop would have 
used six or seven minutes of fuel 
from the misapproach to fuel burnout the plane took a little 
over eight minutes 
the avianca crash seems to be strikingly similar to the crash of 
united airlines dc8 in portland oregon in december 1978 both 
were due to fuel exhaustion 
the ntsb determined that the probable cause of the united 
airlines accident was the failure of the captain to monitor 
properly the aircrafts fuel state and to properly respond to the 
low fuel state according to a ntsb report on the accident 
the board found that the united pilots inattention resulted 
from preoccupation with a landing gear malfunction 
contributing to the portland accident the report stated was 
the failure of the other two flight crew members either to fully 
comprehend the criticality of the fuel state or to successfully 
communicate their concern to the pilot 
the ntsb investigation of the avianca accident is said to be 
focusing on the coordination and communications among the pilot 
copilot and flight engineer 
a report on the probable cause of the avianca accident is 
expected in about 10 months 
mike benson a spokesman for the ntsb and fred farrar a 
spokesman for the federal aviation administration were not in 
their offices when phoned late monday afternoon and did not 
immediately return calls for comment 
</TEXT>
