<TEXT>
pan am customers including a couple 
whose daughter died in the bombing of flight 103 sued the airline 
monday claiming it collected surcharges for a security system that 
was never developed 
the lawsuit charged that millions of pan am passengers between 
1986 and 1989 were defrauded by the 5aticket security surcharge 
on transatlantic flights and an advertising campaign on the 
development of the security system 
after enticing the traveling public into purchasing tickets on 
pan am flights and subsidizing a supposedly efficient security 
system defendants made conscious decisions not to create that 
system the lawsuit alleged 
the lawsuit filed in superior court was intended as a class 
action for customers who purchased tickets affected by the case 
said richard a grossman the attorney handling the case 
the lawsuit also alleges that a private consultant hired by pan 
am in 1986 to review security warned the airline was vulnerable to 
terrorist attack the consultant warned that the advertising 
campaign touting beefedup flight security could be considered 
fraudulent unless changes were made grossman said 
the plaintiffs included peter and aphrodite tsairis of franklin 
lakes and the estate of their daughter alexia tsairis a syracuse 
university undergraduate killed when pan am flight 103 exploded 
over lockerbie scotland on dec 21 1988 the downing of the 
boeing 747 killed all 259 passengers and crew and 11 people on the 
ground 
damages could amount to over 100 million with more than a 
million passengers in line for refunds plus punitive damages 
grossman said 
pan am said in a statement issued by its legal department that 
the lawsuits attempt to recover damages for the death of ms 
tsairis would be handled like all other such claims 
but the company said there was absolutely no merit to the 
lawsuits classaction claims company spokeswoman elizabeth 
manners said pan am would make a motion to dismiss that aspect of 
the lawsuit 
ms manners said about 18 million was collected in 1989 through 
the security surcharges but could not provide amounts for earlier 
years the spokeswoman said the airline spent nearly 47 million on 
security last year 
another plaintiff was t jennifer vail a 20yearold law 
student from wilmington del with no connection to the crash ms 
vail is a pan am customer seeking reimbursement of the surcharges 
and represents others like her grossman said 
the lawsuit alleges the airlines own security expert isaac 
yeffet former head of security for el al airlines in israel told 
pan am officials almost two years before the flight 103 crash that 
the carriers security was almost totally ineffectual 
named as defendants were pan am corp and its subsidiaries pan 
american world airways inc and pan american world services inc 
also named were alert management systems inc a pan am security 
subcontractor c edward acker a former pan am president and chief 
executive officer of pan am and martin e shugrue jr a former 
vice chairman of the corporation and chief executive officer of pan 
am world airways as well as the directors of each company 
james stengel a new york attorney who has defended aircraft 
manufacturers in similar litigation said class actions against 
airlines are not unusual but connecting the surcharge with a fraud 
allegation is a novel approach 
most claims filed against pan am by relatives of flight 103 
victims have been wrongful death and personal injury cases and 
have been combined into a single case he said 
pan am was fined 630000 for security and other violations 
discovered by the federal aviation administration following the 
crash the company has challenged much of the fine which is 
pending said ms manners 
