<TEXT>
an environmental protection agency regional 
official said monday he will recommend that denvers proposed two 
forks dam be vetoed because of the damage it would cause to the 
environment 
the 615foothigh dam to be built near the confluence of the 
south platte river and its north fork would flood 30 miles of 
scenic river valley and canyon and the town of deckers to provide 
drinking water for up to 360000 new denverarea residents 
opponents including several environmental groups have called 
the project the biggest ecological disaster in colorado history 
it appears the godzilla of water projects has met its match 
said dan luecke director of the boulderbased environmental 
defense fund 
lee dehihns the epa deputy regional administrator from atlanta 
who reviewed the project said he would recommend that it be vetoed 
because its adverse impact on fishery wildlife and recreation 
areas would be so significant that these resources would be lost 
forever 
the final decision will be made at epa headquarters in 
washington dc but dehihns has said vetoes are rarely overturned 
epa administrator william reillys designee lujuana wilcher the 
agencys assistant administrator for water has 60 days to affirm 
deny or modify dehihns decision unless an extension is granted 
asked at a news conference if the project is now effectively 
dead dehihns replied nothing is dead until the fat lady sings 
as they say lujuana is not fat but she will make the final 
decision 
dehihns said in his recommendation he is convinced the project 
would cause unacceptable environmental damage including the 
flooding of a trout stream and the loss of highquality habitat 
that is home to deer elk and bighorn sheep 
the epa says there were several alternatives for providing water 
to denvers metropolitan area without causing as much environmental 
damage those include smaller dams water exchanges conservation 
measures and increased use of groundwater 
bill miller manager of the denver water department described 
dehihns recommendation as no surprise and said water officials 
planned to seek consultation at the washington level with the 
decisionmaker back there 
the dam estimated to cost between 500 million and 1 billion 
was proposed by the denver water board and about 42 metropolitan 
water suppliers as the solution to the areas future water needs 
last march reilly announced his intention to veto the project 
and appointed dehihns to oversee the final review of the project 
and to make a final recommendation on its fate 
sen bob kerry dneb said dehihns decision means we will 
have to conserve as well as develop in the future 
with the epas decision to continue the veto process two 
forks is about to return to the obscurity it so richly deserves 
said luecke 
