denzel washington completed his journey from 
television to the movie screen with a best supporting actor oscar 
for his role as a soldier in a black regiment in the civil war 
story glory 
washington becomes the fourth black performer to win an oscar 
for best actor or supporting actor 
washington was an oscar nominee once before as supporting actor 
for his role as steven biko in richard attenboroughs 1987 movie 
cry freedom but he was most widely known for his role on the 
tv series st elsewhere 
my son said he was going to make one of these out of clay for 
me now ive got the model for him washington said in accepting 
his academy award at the music center monday night 
previous black winners were hattie mcdaniel for gone with the 
wind in 1939 and louis gossett jr for an officer and a 
gentleman in 1982 in supporting categories and sidney poitier 
for lilies of the field in 1963 as lead actor 
glory is the story of the formation of the black 54th 
regiment in the union army during the civil war its soldiers 
struggle for respect and its heroic but fatal charge on a 
confederate fort in south carolina 
washington played trip an embittered runaway slave who joins 
the 54th but remains cynical about the undertaking in one of his 
most powerful scenes he tells a fellow enlisted man 
let me tell you something boy you can march like the white 
man you can talk like him you can learn his songs you can even 
wear his suits but you aint never goin to be nothin to him 
washington concluded his thanks for the oscar by paying homage 
to the 54th the black soldiers who helped to make this country 
free 
