nearly 59000 us airline flights were canceled 
last year a 42 percent increase over 1988 according to a report 
published monday 
the cancellations by 12 major carriers for nonmechanical 
reasons left passengers stranded on 58879 domestic flights in the 
year ending jan 31 up from 41448 for the year ending jan 31 
1989 the saint paul pioneer press reported 
us transportation department officials declined to discuss the 
figures which the newspaper said it obtained through a freedom of 
information act request 
of the six largest carriers usair had the worst record with 
both the largest number of cancellations 15849 and the 
greatest increase from the year ending jan 31 1989 its number 
rose by 8758 as it struggled through a merger last fall with 
piedmont airlines 
next was american airlines with an increase of 5033 
cancellations to 10001 and united airlines with an increase of 
3330 to 9190 
northwest airlines had a better record than usair united and 
american canceling only 11 percent of all flights its number of 
cancellations dropped to 5081 last year from 5504 the year before 
officials say weather is a greater problem than it once was 
because airlines are increasingly reliant on hubandspoke systems 
that dispatch many flights from a single city 
bad weather at one hub can mean hundreds of added cancellations 
a day said united spokeswoman sara dornacker she said uniteds 
increased cancellations were due largely to weather but she said 
some of uniteds trouble stems from mechanical problems that delay 
the timely arrival of crews which means canceling more flights 
others said uniteds performance during three months last summer 
may have been affected by laborcontract tensions that kept crews 
from reporting for duty and resulted in crew shortages 
american airlines did not respond to an inquiry on the matter 
friday 
</TEXT>
