<TEXT>
three days after the usbacked 
contras signed an agreement to disband by midapril rebels were 
streaming into nicaragua monday and there were reports of 
intensified fighting 
international observers and witnesses said contra bases across 
the border from nicaragua in yamales honduras were practically 
empty 
they have become ghost camps theres just a few of them left 
there said one international observer who spoke on condition of 
anonmity 
journalists who visited the camps last week had similar reports 
the contra leader who negotiated the demobilization pact oscar 
sovalbarro said 2000 rebel fighters have returned since the 
accord was signed friday 
he said a 2000person insurgent military contingent is 
already back in nicaragua and its numbers could increase at any 
moment 
the movement of rebel fighters into nicaragua could undermine 
hopes raised by the accord which establishes a demobilization 
deadline only for the contras in honduras 
in miami the top contra military commander israel galeano 
insisted the fighters in nicaragua would not disarm until the 
sandinista army does 
we are speaking of total demobilization that includes both 
ourselves and the sandinistas he said 
sandinista leaders have said their party will not turn over 
control of the army to the new government unless the usbacked 
contras demobilize 
galeano who did not sign the accord said it was unrealistic to 
expect the contras to demobilize immediately an eightyear 
process cannot be decided by the dismantlement of an organization 
in 15 days he said 
the defense ministry says there have been at least two clashes 
between the army and the contras since friday in which 16 people 
died 
the ministry also said about 100 contras seized a truck sunday 
night robbed the passengers of cash and jewelry and made the owner 
pay a 500 ransom to get the vehicle back 
all the incidents took place near the provincial capital of 
jinotega 100 miles northeast of managua on the honduran border 
international observers say there appears to be a split among 
the contras over the pact but sovalbarro and galeano denied any 
rift 
at the moment we are a very solid organization we mutually 
support each other galeano said 
sovalbarro and a spokesman for galeano alejandro acevdeo 
denied there had been an increase in fighting and said the 
sandinistas were lying 
it is the sandinistas who are trying to undermine the peace 
process we think the sandinistas are disguising themselves and 
staging attacks to discredit us acevedo said 
the demobilization agreement signed friday in the honduran 
capital of tegucigalpa between representatives of the rebels and of 
the incoming government of the united national opposition alliance 
or uno calls for an immediate ceasefire 
it says the contras in honduras will demobilize by april 20 
five days before presidentelect violeta barrios de chamorro takes 
office 
most of the 12000man contra army that holed up in honduras 
after us military aid ended in 1988 began returning to nicaragua 
in september as many as 4000 were believed to be in nicaragua by 
the feb 25 election 
the demobilization pact says the contras inside nicaragua will 
move into secure zones monitored by the united nations and 
cardinal miguel obando y bravo the archbishop of managua 
the accord was signed by sovalbarro but not by galeano one 
foreign observer interpreted this as a loophole should galeano 
also known as commander franklyn decide not to adhere to the pact 
the agreement reached with the new government of nicaragua 
surprised our combatants at first sovalbarro acknowledged but 
now we are all happy over what happened 
the observer speaking on condition of anonymity said there 
appeared to be a split between contra forces loyal to franklyn 
galeano and followers of sovalbarro ruben 
we have estimated that franklyn controls about 40 percent of 
the contras and ruben about 60 percent and that franklyn is the 
toughest of the two said the observer maybe ruben wants to 
demobilize but not franklyn 
president daniel ortega has also said he was concerned that 
galeano had not signed the accord 
franklyns brother osvaldo galeano commander negro told the 
associated press last week that his forces would not demobilize 
unless the sandinista army and interior ministry did the same 
in the first reported clash after the pact was signed about 100 
contras friday ambushed an undisclosed number of sandinistas in la 
pavona 33 miles northeast of jinotega the defense ministry said 
12 sandinista soldiers and four contras were killed and eight 
sandinista soldiers and civilians were wounded in a 90minute 
firefight 
the defense ministry also reported a 30minute firefight sunday 
evening between about 30 contras and sandinista troops no 
casualities were reported 
jinotega province is the northern tip of a corridor used by the 
contras to infiltrate nicaragua the contras are supported by 
peasants in the corridor a strip extending south through the 
middle of nicaragua to the costa rican border 
