<TEXT>
the american society of newspaper editors on march 
20 criticized defense secretary dick cheneys delay in alerting the 
16member press pool of the us invasion of panama last december 
cheneys decision to delay calling the pool until after the 
close of office hours and the broadcast of the evening news made 
assembling the pool difficult and actually increased the security 
problem said jean otto chairman of the asnes pressbarpublic 
affairs committee 
it also assured that the pool would not arrive until hours 
after the invasion was launched on dec 20 otto associate 
editor of the rocky mountain news said in a news release 
the asne statement came as a pentagonsponsored report was 
released saying us reporters missed the start of the invasion 
because cheney decided secrecy was more important than ensuring 
news coverage 
the report also criticized cheneys press secretary pete 
williams for not trying to convince the secretary to send a group 
of reporters and photographers to panama in time to cover the 
critical opening battles 
i take the blame for what happened in panama williams said 
in response to the report 
he said the defense department was fully committed to the idea 
of allowing the news media to cover military operations and that 
steps already were being taken to correct problems described in the 
latest study 
a pool system was established by representatives of the pentagon 
and the news media after the 1983 invasion of grenada it is 
designed to have objective observers inform american citizens from 
the start of military actions involving us personnel 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
ingersoll newspapers inc has offered to 
buy back 159 million of its junk bonds at discounted prices as it 
tries to meet interest payments 
ingersoll newspapers a subsidiary of ingersoll publications 
inc offered march 22 to buy the bonds at between 25 percent and 
55 percent of the principal amount 
one series of bonds has been trading at about 400 per 1000 in 
face value a separate series is trading at about 200 per 1000 
ingersoll owns 19 daily newspapers in the united states and 
great britain and also operates a dozen groups of weekly 
newspapers most situated in the same cities as ingersoll daily 
newspapers 
junk bond analyst ned zachar of duff amp phelps inc in chicago 
said ingersoll like other newspaper companies in the northeastern 
united states is facing financial problems from an overall 
economic slowdown ingersoll spokesman mark harnett said earnings 
have fallen off 
zachar said bondholders should accept some kind of offer to 
avoid pushing the publishing company into bankruptcy but he 
expected a higher purchase price to result from any negotiations 
i think theres a pretty good chance ingersoll will succeed 
with a tender offer he said but whether it will be at this 
price or another remains to be seen the bondholders will likely 
push for a little more 
