<TEXT>
human rights advocate natan sharansky 
criticized israels censorship of reports on soviet immigration 
saying it was hurting efforts to settle the new arrivals 
sharansky a former soviet refusnik was joined by an official 
of a resettlement agency in complaining about excessive censorship 
march 20 
the ban on publication of immigration figures was imposed march 
1 amid mounting arab protests the influx could lead to more jewish 
settlement in the israelioccupied west bank and gaza strip home 
to 17 million palestinians 
sharansky who heads the soviet jewry zionist forum said some 
selfcensorship might be needed to ensure the security of the 
immigrants 
but he said we need more support from world jewry and to 
make bureaucrats work more effectively we need more public 
pressure we cant do it under conditions of censorship 
sharansky and other israeli activists have said the jewish state 
is not preparing enough housing and jobs for the arriving soviets 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the chairman of polands largest press 
cooperative said march 21 the solidarityled government had acted 
unfairly in deciding that it be liquidated 
under communist rule the workers publishing cooperative 
muzzled unauthorized publications on march 19 the cabinet decided 
to do away with the group because it was seen as an organ of the 
nowdefunct communist party 
parliament must still pass the law dismantling the group 
slawomir tabkowski chairman of the cooperative said the 
government commission that developed the law had submitted to 
neobolshevik pressure aimed at attaining political revenge 
he said the cooperative had gotten only a brief chance to 
display its plans to reform itself and the government had made an 
arbitrary decision 
the cooperative published the vast majority of newspapers on the 
market controlled the sale of newspapers through its monopoly on 
more than 20000 kiosks in the country and owned several important 
publishing houses 
last year the popularity of the cooperatives publications 
began to drop as new independent newspapers emerged in polands 
changing political climate 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
some broadcasts by radio vilnius voice of the 
lithuanian capital have been blocked by the soviet union since the 
lithuanian parliament declared independence a state radio report 
march 19 said 
a radio vilnius announcer suggested that the soviet ministry of 
communications was responsible and asked listeners in europe to 
tune to frequencies that are not relayed by radio moscow 
today the leaders of the lithuanian radio and tv networks and 
radio vilnius people have been getting in touch with highlevel or 
ranking officials of radio moscow said the announcer who by 
custom in that country was not identified it appears the 
blockade of radio vilnius broadcasts was a surprise to them and 
they promised to clear up what the matter was 
the agencys shortwave broadcasts to north america normally are 
made on six different frequencies to ensure a good chance of 
reception in all areas of the continent 
the broadcasts are normally relayed by radio moscow on its 
powerful transmitters 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the government said march 22 it is 
lifting bans on two newspapers and a roman catholic radio station 
that had been accused of reporting false information 
president samuel doe decided to remove the ban in honor of 
namibias independence that day according to a ministry of 
information statement the southern african nation became 
independent after 75 years of white south african rule 
footprints today and sun times newspapers were banned in april 
1988 when the government also barred radio stations from 
broadcasting reports of the british broadcasting corp and the 
usfunded voice of america 
footprints today was accused of fabricating a letter to the 
editor signed by an alleged army officer who said secret killings 
and arrests were increasing in liberia 
offending stories in the sun times reported the arrest of a 
ghanaian for possession of explosives and the firing of the 
commander of a government antiterrorist squad 
elcm community radio was ordered closed in june 1989 for 
reporting one person was crushed to death and hundreds were injured 
in a stampede at a monrovia football stadium where liberia lost to 
malawi 
the independent press of this west african nation which was 
founded by freed american slaves in 1847 expressed anger march 17 
over the burning down of the independent daily observer newspaper 
building 
four armed men in military uniforms reportedly doused the 
library darkroom and newsroom with gasoline then set them ablaze 
newspaper editors said the act was intended to intimidate them 
also last week the managing director of the independent news 
klon hinneh was detained for several days under a court order for 
printing chief justice emmanuel gbalazehs picture on the back page 
instead of the front page 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
some of the biggest players in west german 
journalism have begun selling magazines and newspapers in east 
germany 
eastern publishers knew when the government of erich honecker 
fell in october that wed be faced with freemarket competition 
that wed have to adopt more competitive practices said matthias 
schlegel deputy editor of the daily neue zeit 
his newspaper with a circulation of 150000 and a price of 20 
pfennigs 12 cents has survived only with state support 
were worried we wont be able to survive economically 
schlegel said its a real question for our existence he said 
early this month west german publishers put street vendors to 
work in a major east berlin plaza selling such journals as the 
masscirculation bild zeitung conservative daily die welt news 
magazines der spiegel and stern and a wide range of fashion and 
sports magazines 
the western publications can be expensive under a typical 
pricing formula der spiegel would cost 1350 east marks the 
equivalent of 765 
schlegel said there may be a spate of takeovers by west german 
press barons jockeying for market position and that small regional 
or local papers might be targets 
other changes the east german news agency adn which surprised 
western journalists with its rapid change to fast reliable 
reporting is said to be planning a merger with the west german 
agency dpa and tageszeitung a west german tabloid has set up in 
east berlin to print a separate eastern edition 
</TEXT>
