<TEXT>
a havana radio speech by cuban president fidel 
castro was picked up on at least six am radio frequencies in 
florida march 23 in what may be a prelude to a coldwar battle over 
usfinanced tv marti 
the cuban communist party newspaper granma mentioned in its 
march 23 editions that castros remarks would be broadcast toward 
the united states that evening 
wyfx in delray beach was one of the stations affected 
i have been getting some feedback over the air said disc 
jockey lorenzo fox you hear some kind of broadcast coming 
through 
other stations such as spanishlanguage wqba in miami and wvcg 
in coral gables responded to the interference by boosting their 
signal 
others were not seriously affected because they are normally off 
the air at night 
tv marti is expected to begin within weeks the cuban government 
has threatened to jam us broadcast transmissions if the 
television service is beamed toward cuba 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the federal communications commission on march 
21 further narrowed the field of contestants seeking to market a 
highdefinition television transmission system 
chairman alfred sikes said the fcc voted to consider only 
systems that will not require use of an extra augmentation 
channel 
only socalled simulcast systems will be considered for testing 
at the advanced television test center this fall sikes said 
in a simulcast system a tv station would broadcast its regular 
signal on one channel and the same program on another channel in 
highdefinition 
augmentation systems also use two channels but use the second 
channel to provide a signal that when combined in the tv set with 
the regular signal on the first channel yields the highdefinition 
picture 
peter fannon executive director of the test center said five 
entrants have been accepted for the test so far sarnoffphilips 
an analog simulcast system from philips zenith electronics corp 
and the narrow muse and muse6 systems from the japan broadcasting 
corp 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
abc said march 21 it plans to show 20 percent 
fewer commercials when its new twin peaks series premieres as a 
twohour special on april 8 
the decision could cost the network up to 650000 spokeswoman 
janice gretemeyer said abc had considered airing the special 
without commercials to draw attention to the series created by 
filmmaker david lynch 
but it decided that would have been too expensive and chose 
instead to cut back on commercials she said the premiere will 
have 11 minutes and 12 seconds of commercials instead of the usual 
14 minutes for sunday movies 
richard kostrya an executive vice president of the j walter 
thompson advertising agency estimated that abcs decision could 
cost the network from 600000 to 650000 the network did not 
provide an estimate 
the series set in the pacific northwest is described by abc as 
a sometimes darkly comic vision of commonplace things and 
events 
lynch is known for such dark works as the movie blue velvet 
</TEXT>
