<TEXT>
the setting is a tiny pittsburgh 
restaurant a month after the death of martin luther king jr but 
august wilsons latest work in his cycle of plays about black 
america is not about the turbulent 1960s 
people have written so much about the 60s so i didnt need 
to do that i went at it obliquely said wilson whose play 
two trains running premieres march 30 at the yale repertory 
theater 
in his fifth collaboration with director lloyd richards the 
acclaimed playwright returns to a dominant theme in all his works 
to have a future blacks in america must first define who they are 
by reclaiming their past 
unless you reconnect to your past make some accommodation to 
your past fully understand your history in the world you cant 
have a future said the 44yearold wilson 
two trains running its title taken from a blues song of the 
same name is filled with references to death one of the 
restaurants patrons is an undertaker whose funeral parlor is 
across the street as the characters talk about the conditions of 
their lives wilson said what you find is people are dying 
infant mortality rates are high police are shooting people drugs 
are killing people everyone is dying young 
quickly what you discover is that the real problem is the 
economic problem there simply are not any jobs for any of these 
people in pittsburgh in 1968 you could have written the same thing 
for the 1980s things havent changed at all they have actually 
got worse 
wilson was born in pittsburgh but has lived in st paul minn 
since 1978 
in the play everything seems to be working against memphis the 
restaurant owner and the other characters memphis is a former 
sharecropper who was run out of mississippi in 1931 and whose 
restaurant is about to be torn down 
but in the middle of all this loss and death is that which does 
not die tradition the main characters tap into that by going to 
see aunt esther a woman who claims to be 322 years old 
aunt esther an offstage character will make you right with 
your self said wilson who with his raspy smokers voice 
frequently draws from the plays dialogue to illustrate a point 
aunt esther tells memphis if he drops the ball there is no 
need to continue to run because if you get to the end zone there is 
not going to be a touchdown youve got to go back and pick up the 
ball each of the characters gets the same message youve got to 
go back and claim what is yours before you can go forward 
at a meat market next to the funeral home a man walks in and 
tells the owner i want my ham he says take a chicken for 
the past nine years every morning this guy has been showing up for 
me that represents black america standing patiently outside the 
door of american society in 1968 and prior to that i want my ham 
i want my ham wilson said 
while two trains running is set in the 60s wilsons other 
major works have addressed issues facing american blacks during 
other decades of this century all have premiered at yale with 
richards directing the theatrical partnership began in 1984 with 
ma raineys black bottom 1920s and continued with fences 
1950s joe turners come and gone 191020 and the piano 
lesson 1930s which opens on broadway on april 16 
wilson won a tony and the pulitzer prize for fences 
richards received a tony for best director for the play wilson 
also won the new york drama critics circle award for three of his 
plays 
with richards tenure as dean of the yale school of drama and 
artistic director at the yale rep ending in june 1991 two 
trains could be the last of wilsons plays to have its premiere 
at yale but wilson said it definitely will not be their last 
collaboration wherever he goes thats where im going 
the collaboration has made his string of plays seem seamless he 
said they are all the same in the sense you have the same 
artistic sensibilities working on the play 
weve developed over the course of the years a kind of 
shorthand way of working there is not a lot of talking that goes 
on 
wilson believes he is getting better with each play he writes 
he said myth and ritual are also growing to be larger elements 
citing the tall tale of the 3centuryold woman as an example 
ive learned a lot about building characters i know what is 
important now he said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

