in a report last fall to defense secretary dick cheney the 
pentagons defense advisory committee on women in the services 
said the services can ill afford to continue to limit these 
women and their experiences in the face of the anticipated manpower 
shortages of the 1990s 
by comparing sheer statistics women seem to fare best in the 
air force 
the services hightech longdistance weaponry allows for 97 
percent of its specialities to be open to women with 136 percent 
of its force being female 
women are barred from serving in fighters bombers tactical 
airlift cargo planes and some helicopters but they are allowed to 
fly in some transport aircraft in commandpost aircraft on 
reconnaisance aircraft and on support missions 
the air force recently lifted the restrictions against women 
flying on c130 and c141 transports that drop paratroopers into 
battle zones 
the army is 114 percent female the advertising directed at 
recruiting women boasts that more than 93 percent of its 
specialities are open to women given the services high combat 
needs however this translates to about half of its job slots 
being closed to women 
the army after more than a year of indecision still hasnt 
decided what to do with some 345 women whove been trained as field 
artillery officers but whove been pulled from their jobs amid 
worries that the positions would be too exposed to enemy fire 
the navy at a 99 percent female level bars women from serving 
on all aircraft carriers except one the uss lexington a training 
ship while combat vessels such as destroyers and cruisers are also 
offlimits women do serve at sea on support ships such as oilers 
and tenders that supply aircraft carriers submarines and other 
fighting vessels 
the marine corps has the smallest percentage of slots open to 
women 48 percent marine corps officials point out that because 
the service relies on the navy for medical care the marines dont 
have a large number of nurses a traditionally female specialty in 
the armed services 
questions about the future role of women in the military have 
grown sharper not only because of the attention focused on the 
hundreds of women who participated in the panama invasion but also 
because of the extensive personnel cuts the pentagon faces in light 
of the nations budget woes and the end of the cold war 
two congresswomen say they want to ensure that military women 
dont suffer disproportionately under the manpower cuts that seem 
virtually certain with the easing of eastwest tension 
rep patricia schroeder dcolo has introduced legislation 
that would allow army women to apply for all positions including 
combatrelated slots 
polls show seven out of 10 americans think women should have a 
chance to serve in combat units if they want to ms schroeder 
says its a really touchy issue but weve had women die in 
combat and i think the american people are aware of what that 
means 
rep beverly bryon dmd chairman of the house armed services 
subcommittee on military personnel says that while more job 
categories should be open to women she opposes the idea of them 
entering combat units 
were moving along at a pace im comfortable with mrs 
byron says 
the service academies west point annapolis and the air force 
academy began graduating women only 10 years ago so few have had 
time to reach the higher decisionmaking ranks of the military 
at the end of last year only seven women held the rank of 
general or admiral 
were still in the process of aging the officer corps says 
foote its going to take us a while to get women where they can 
make more than just token changes in the way the military is run 
