monday in london down from 38695 late friday earlier in hong 
kong gold fell 549 to close at a bid of 38494 an ounce 
among the rumored big sellers was the saudia arabian monetary 
agency which was said to have bought british pounds with the 
proceeds from selling an estimated 3 million troy ounces the 
agency acts as the countrys central bank and is the main 
repository of hard currencies and gold reserves 
japanese institutions reportedly unloaded gold to raise cash for 
buying stocks the tokyo stock exchanges key index soared by 
nearly 5 percent monday in its secondbiggest singleday rise ever 
rebounding slightly from this years severe slump 
it has been widely assumed that the japanese had been selling 
gold for months possibly to cover stock losses 
market reports also said the soviet union sold gold to raise 
money to help it cope with economic difficulties 
john p norris manager of the precious metals department at 
citibank in new york said returns on currencies have become 
increasingly attractive due to rising interest rates 
there has been liquidation by large gold investors to take 
advantage of higher yields elsewhere he said 
silver also was under pressure silver for march delivery fell 
to 4955 a troy ounce on new yorks comex from 5043 friday 
earlier in london silver fell to a bid of 495 an ounce from 
504 late friday marking the first time silver closed below 5 an 
ounce there since june 30 1986 
the dollar has been bid up due to speculation that us interest 
rates will remain at present levels or higher there is a 
perception the federal reserve wont nudge rates down because 
economic growth appears adequate while inflationary pressures 
persist 
