<TEXT>
olympic federal a little old midwestern thrift 
that wants to stay around another 100 years is trying to ensure 
its future by pressing ahead with a lawsuit against federal 
regulators chairman john j lanigan said monday 
olympic one of about 600 of 2600 sampls nationally that fall 
short of federal capital requirements sued to stop the treasury 
departments office of thrift supervision from taking it over that 
suit initially upheld by a district court judge threatened to 
disrupt the bush administrations bailout of the thrift industry by 
prompting a flood of similar suits 
however the us court of appeals for the district of columbia 
circuit moved to avoid such a deluge friday when it lifted an 
injunction against a takeover of olympic saying the harm to the 
public outweighs the harm to olympic in this instance 
olympic officials and attorneys are not upset by the reversal 
because the decision prohibits the thrift office from liquidating 
the suburban chicago sampl and selling its 11 billion in assets 
what officials of the berwynbased olympic want from the lawsuit 
is about 100 million that they believe the government owes them a 
sum that will enable them to accept a friendly buyout offer said 
lanigan 
were not asking for anything that shouldnt be coming to 
us he said 
olympic also is asking the court to bar the thrift office from 
initiating a takeover until after the federal deposit insurance 
corp rules on the purchase of the thrift by a bank holding 
company said olympic attorney charles j cooper 
the government has taken over more than 120 sampls since the 
bailout began and is expected to seize as many as 200 more 
institutions 
olympic contends that last years sampl bailout legislation 
unfairly wiped out an accounting measure known as supervisory 
good will dropping olympic below the capital requirements 
cooper said 
before the sampl legislation the government permitted an 
institution that bought an insolvent thrift to count as capital the 
difference between assets and liabilities of the failed sampl cooper 
said that amount known as supervisory good will was to 
amortized or written off over time 
at least four lawsuits have been filed against the government 
protesting the reversal on good will said thrift office spokesman 
paul lockwood 
olympic took over seven insolvent sampls in the early 1980s and 
tallied 160 million in good will to be written off over about 40 
years lanigan said writing off 6 million per year the thrift 
now has 115 in good will capital that no longer counts 
they took what we used to count as an asset on our balance 
sheet all we want to say is reimburse us lanigan said 
olympics lawsuit seeks the restoration of the good will 
accounting measure or a government reimbursement 
the thrifts suitor whom lanigan declined to name is willing 
to inject 30 million to 40 million into olympic if the good will 
is restored or reimbursed by the government lanigan said 
no investor is going to come in and buy an asset that isnt 
recognized by the government he said 
another court hearing on olympics suit is set for april 11 
olympics suit also challenged the constitutionality of 
takeovers on the grounds that the director appointed as part of the 
bailout legislation and his replacement were not nominated by the 
president and confirmed by the senate as provided by the 
constitution 
it was on these grounds that the district court judge barred the 
federal takeover of olympic 
that argument would be moot for olympic if t timonty ryan jr 
a former labor department attorney is confirmed as thrift office 
director ryan has been nominated for a fiveyear term and the 
senate banking committee has scheduled a confirmation hearing for 
wednesday 
