<TEXT>
the united states and european economic 
community are considering an international agreement to settle 
possible jurisdictional disputes once internal european trade 
barriers are removed in 1992 vice president sir leon brittan of 
the european commission said monday 
at present there is no means of resolving such a dispute 
brittan said i therefore think that we now need to give serious 
consideration to the desirability of a treaty or less formal 
agreement between the community and the united states to deal with 
such problems 
brittan said the tearing down of nontariff barriers under a 
single integrated market system in 1992 will intensify european 
competition with the united states such a treaty would pertain to 
competition involving mergers within the economic community 
brittan the european community commissioner in charge of 
financial services and competition made the remarks in a speech to 
the ec chambers of commerce in new york where he wound up a 
oneweek visit to the united states 
the commission is the joint executive body of the 12 member 
countries 
brittan said he met with various us cabinet members and 
lawmakers in washington during his visit including assistant 
attorney general james rill with whom he discussed the proposed 
treaty 
i was encouraged by his positive reaction and we will now be 
working up our ideas in detail so that they can be properly 
considered on both sides of the atlantic he said 
brittan said the substance of any such agreement would still 
have to be formulated 
such an agreement would provide for information gathering and 
exchange and would lay down a detailed procedure for consultations 
on cases and issues of common interest he said 
it might even contain an arbitration clause although the 
political difficulties of getting that agreed should not be 
underestimated 
