<TEXT>
new yorks budget woes took a dramatic turn 
for the worse monday as wall streets two major rating agencies 
lowered the states credit rating leaving it with the third worst 
rating among the 50 states 
the credit downgradings could cost new york taxpayers millions 
of dollars in higher interest payments on the states debt only 
massachusetts and louisiana are rated as worse credit risks than 
new york now 
were behind west virginia for christs sake complained 
state comptroller edward regan 
regan a republican said he would not help democratic gov 
mario cuomo and the legislature balance the books for the coming 
budget year by jiggering the contribution formula for the states 
public employee pension system 
cuomo has blamed the states third straight year of fiscal 
problems on an unanticipated drop in state revenues stemming from 
the 1986 federal tax reform act and the economic slowdown that has 
hit the northeast 
the states budget deficit for fiscal 1990 which ends saturday 
is projected at more than 1 billion and a forecast gap of 15 
billion for fiscal 1991 continues to grow standard amp poors 
corp said in announcing its downgrade 
both standard amp poors and moodys investors service inc 
dropped their credit ratings on the 775 million in shortterm 
funds the state will borrow on tuesday to balance this years 
budget the new ratings are one notch lower than ratings for 
budgetbalancing loans taken out a year ago 
standard amp poors also went one step further and lowered the 
rating on new yorks longterm debt by two notches to the lowest 
level in state history 
the agency lowered the ratings because there are no responsible 
solutions in sight for new yorks chronic fiscal imbalance sampp 
analyst hyman grossman said 
obviously the situation has gotten materially worse and the 
solution is a bigger hurdle than it was only a few months ago 
grossman said 
the move by standard amp poors reduced the states longterm 
credit rating from doubleaminus to singlea 
during the fiscal crisis of the mid1970s when new york city 
nearly went bankrupt standard amp poors rated the states credit at 
aa three notches higher than the new rating 
but state officials and analysts said the new rating didnt 
necessarily indicate that the current fiscal problems are worse 
than the crisis of 15 years ago 
moodys did not change its longterm credit rating for new york 
but analyst george leung said the agency would be watching the 
state closely moodys currently gives new york a rating of a1 
which is roughly comparable to sampps new singlea rating 
an a is a mediocre rating leung said 
the sampp downgrade affected the states 39 billion in 
outstanding general obligation bonds new york has a total of more 
than 20 billion of various types of debt outstanding 
a lower bond rating typically forces borrowers to pay a higher 
interest rate to sell its debt 
cuomo said the lower rating on tuesdays shortterm borrowing 
alone would cost the state an additional 10 million in interest 
the continuing delay in achieving progress on a new state 
budget has now taken its toll on taxpayers as i have warned for 
weeks that it would cuomo said in a statement 
cuomo and assembly speaker mel miller also a democrat are 
locked in a battle with the state senates republican majority over 
whether higher taxes are needed to help close the mounting budget 
deficit 
standard amp poors criticized cuomo and legislative leaders for 
failing to agree on the size of the states budget problem and to 
devise a credible plan to address it in a fiscally responsible 
manner 
the budget is supposed to be in place by the start of the 
states fiscal year which begins on sunday but that hasnt 
happened since 1984 
</TEXT>
